d, United Kingdom","England":"England, Frogn, Akershus, Norway","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Stallingborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Stallingborough, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Irnham, Lincolnshire, England":"Irnham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joan Taillebois was born about 1365, in England, Frogn, Akershus, Norway, her father, Henry Tailboys, was 32 and her mother, Eleanor Burradon, was 34. She married Andrew Luttrell Jr about 1390, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died before 1397."},"et":{"about 1365–BEF    1397":"umbes 1365–enne 1397","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1365–1397":"1365–1397","1364–1397":"1364–1397","1383–1418":"1383–1418","1393–1422":"1393–1422","1335–1369":"1335–1369","1333–1381":"1333–1381","about 1393":"umbes 1393","about 1390":"umbes 1390","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1381":"1381","23 February 1369":"23. veebruar 1369","1369":"1369","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1333":"1333","1365":"1365","6 January 1381":"6. jaanuar 1381","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","BEF    1397":"enne 1397","about 1365":"umbes 1365","27 October 1383":"27. oktoober 1383","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England, Frogn, Akershus, Norra","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","Stallingborough, Lincolnshire, England":"Stallingborough, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Irnham, Lincolnshire, England":"Irnham, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1365–BEF    1397":"noin 1365–ennen vuotta 1397","1350–1417":"1350–1417","1365–1397":"1365–1397","1364–1397":"1364–1397","1383–1418":"1383–1418","1393–1422":"1393–1422","1335–1369":"1335–1369","1333–1381":"1333–1381","about 1393":"noin 1393","about 1390":"noin 1390","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1393":"1393","1381":"1381","23 February 1369":"23. helmikuuta 1369","1369":"1369","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1333":"1333","1365":"1365","6 January 1381":"6. tammikuuta 1381","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","BEF    1397":"ennen vuotta 1397","about 1365":"noin 1365","27 October 1383":"27. lokakuuta 1383","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England, Frogn,